  sodium: 2010 mg
---

Wash and dry produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%unit}, separating
whites from greens; finely chop greens. Halve, peel, and dice @red onion{1}
(whole onion for 4 servings) into ½-inch pieces.

In a #small bowl{}, combine scallion greens, @sour cream{4.5%tablespoon}, and
@white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}. Stir until smooth. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

Rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water; pat dry with #paper towels{}.
Cut into ¾-inch pieces.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #large pot{} over medium heat. Add diced onion
and scallion whites; cook, stirring, until softened and translucent,
~{4-6%minutes}.

Increase heat to medium high. Add shrimp and @bok choy and napa cabbage{4%ounce};
cook, stirring, until veggies are wilted and shrimp are opaque and mostly
cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} (shrimp will finish cooking in the next step).

To #pot{} with shrimp and veggies, stir in @Szechuan paste{2%tablespoon},
@chicken stock concentrate{1%unit}, half the remaining vinegar
(all for 4 servings), and @water{1 1/4%cups}. Bring to a simmer; cook,
stirring, until shrimp are cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

Remove pot from heat; stir in remaining plain sour cream.

Divide soup between #bowls{}; top with scallion sour cream and
@crispy fried onions{1%unit}. Serve.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.